    [35mpayload[39m: {
      "action": "Launch a formal petition to the city's secular magistrate to convert the Signal-House Families' provisional control of the Night Courier Depot's routing ledger into permanent, exclusive authority. The Families' legal agents present the magistrate with: (1) the original liturgical charter endorsed by the Shrine Auditors' Council, (2) the Lacquer Seal Verification Authority's licensing treaty, (3) documented proof of successful routing operations under their provisional stewardship, and (4) a coalition of forty-seven independent couriers and gondola operators who testify that the Families' system has reduced message delays by 60%. The petition explicitly frames the Families as the only faction capable of neutral, secular administration of the routing ledger — unlike the Wardens (who seek tariff monopoly) or the Council (who seek liturgical control). The Families also quietly offer the magistrate's office guaranteed bandwidth on the Prayer-Signal Array for official city communications, a subtle but powerful incentive.",
      "outcome": "The secular magistrate, facing pressure from multiple factions but impressed by the Families' commercial track record and broad operator support, grants a conditional permanent charter for the Night Courier Depot's routing ledger. The charter is conditional on three requirements: (1) the Families must maintain open access for all licensed couriers regardless of faction affiliation, (2) a 5% revenue share must be remitted to the city treasury, and (3) the charter must be reviewed at the end of each high-water season. The Families accept all conditions — the revenue share is trivial compared to their routing fees, and seasonal review is a formality they can manage. The Guild Wardens, learning of the charter through their informants, file an immediate protest but lack the political capital to challenge it while their own legitimacy remains contested. The Shrine Auditors' Council, preoccupied with Silent Spire negotiations, offers no formal objection — though their silence is born of distraction rather than consent. The Signal-House Families now hold permanent (if conditional) authority over the Canal Market District's most critical message-routing infrastructure. Their control is no longer provisional — it is chartered, documented, and backed by secular law.",
      "targetLocation": "Night Courier Depot",
      "tagChangeCount": 2,
      "chronicleEntryId": "1263a70c-2429-4c49-9752-7a9cc6b4cd3e"
    }
