    [35mpayload[39m: {
      "action": "Convene an emergency demonstration at the Resin Mixing Chamber for Signal-House Families representatives, using the seven copied consecrated seal templates to produce authenticated lacquer seals that pass all triply-authenticated verification tests. The Authority's artificers showcase their independent authentication capability — proving the templates are valid regardless of Council consecration status — and formally propose expanding the licensing treaty to include a \"quadruple authentication\" standard using the Authority's proprietary sealant formula, cementing their monopoly over all lacquer-based message authentication in the Canal Market District.",
      "outcome": "The Signal-House Families' representatives, initially skeptical, are convinced by the demonstration. The seven copied templates produce seals indistinguishable from Council-consecrated originals under all known verification protocols. The Families agree to a revised licensing treaty that establishes the \"quadruple authentication\" standard — incorporating the Authority's proprietary sealant formula as the fourth verification layer. This effectively locks out any competitor lacking access to both the copied templates AND the Authority's sealant chemistry. The Families' unease about tainted standards is replaced by pragmatic acceptance: the templates work, the seals are valid, and the monopoly strengthens their joint commercial position against both the Wardens and the Council. The Authority's reputation among market operators begins to recover — not as a trustworthy institution, but as an indispensable one. The Shrine Auditors' Council, still reeling from the Wardens' intelligence offensive and consumed by Silent Spire negotiations, lacks the bandwidth to challenge the new standard immediately.",
      "targetLocation": "Resin Mixing Chamber",
      "tagChangeCount": 3,
      "chronicleEntryId": "20f84878-e037-42de-b438-990aad8dd1da"
    }
